Illuga frowns. “May you what.”

Siegurd gestures—not to Illuga—but to the bench near his feet.

“To sit.”

Illuga exhales. “You don’t need permission to sit.”

“I do here.”

A pause.

“…Fine.”

Siegurd sits—but lower than necessary, positioning himself near Illuga’s boots.

The shift is subtle.

Intentional.

Illuga notices.

Says nothing.

For a moment, they remain like that—silence stretching, but not uncomfortable.

Then Siegurd reaches forward.

Slowly.

Giving time to refuse.

He rests his hand lightly against Illuga’s ankle.

Stillness.

Illuga does not pull away.

Siegurd begins to unfasten the boot.

Careful. Methodical.

As if the act itself matters.

“Your footing was uneven earlier,” he says quietly. “You compensate when you’re tired.”

Illuga watches him now.

“…You were paying that much attention.”

“Yes.”

The boot comes off.

Siegurd sets it aside with care before moving to the other.

No rush.

No assumption.

Each motion offered—never imposed.

When both boots are removed, Siegurd pauses.

Looks up.

Silent question.

Illuga hesitates.

Then—just slightly—extends his foot.

The permission is small.

But it’s there.

Siegurd accepts it without comment.

His hands are warm despite the cold air.

He works tension out slowly, deliberately—not indulgent, not careless.

Attentive.

Grounding.

Illuga exhales without meaning to.

His shoulders drop a fraction.

The room feels…different.

Quieter.

Not empty.

Held.

Siegurd continues—unwavering, present.

At one point, he shifts slightly, adjusting his position so Illuga’s leg rests more comfortably.

Supporting the weight without asking.

Becoming structure.

Illuga notices that too.

“…You don’t have to do this.”

“I know.”

No hesitation.

No expectation.

Just truth.

That’s what makes it difficult.

Illuga looks away.

But he doesn’t pull back.

And that—

is the change.

