CHAPTER — THE QUIET WAR
The camp was set just beyond the treeline.

Not far from the Palace—close enough that its silhouette loomed through the frost-haze like a watching thing.

No one spoke of the village.

But it clung to them.

Especially to Siegurd.

NIGHT WATCH
The fire burned low.

Most of the men had already turned in, their silhouettes swallowed by canvas and shadow. Only the steady crackle of wood and the distant howl of wind filled the quiet.

Siegurd stood at the edge of the light.

Watching.

Not the forest.

Varka.

The Knight of Favonius sat across the fire, broad shoulders relaxed, one arm draped over his knee, a half-empty flask dangling from his fingers. He looked at ease.

He wasn’t.

Siegurd could see it in the stillness.

In the way his gaze drifted—not outward, but inward.

Calculating.

Weighing.

Remembering.

Siegurd stepped forward.

“We should speak.”

Varka didn’t look up immediately. He took another slow drink, then wiped his mouth with the back of his hand.

“I figured we would,” he said.

His tone was casual.

His eyes were not.

THE OPENING MOVE
Siegurd didn’t sit.

He remained standing—deliberately.

A soldier addressing another.

Not an equal.

Not yet.

“You care for him,” Siegurd said.

No preamble.

No softness.

Varka huffed a quiet breath.

“Which one?”

“Illuga.”

That got his attention.

Varka’s gaze lifted fully now, sharp and assessing.

“And if I do?” he asked.

Siegurd’s voice did not waver.

“Then you should understand what is happening to him.”

Silence stretched.

The fire cracked between them.

Varka leaned back slightly.

“Careful,” he said. “You’re about to start sounding like a man with a point to prove.”

Siegurd met his gaze evenly.

“I don’t need to prove anything.”

A beat.

“I need you to see clearly.”

CONTROL VS DEVOTION
Varka let out a quiet laugh.

“There it is,” he murmured. “Go on, then. Enlighten me.”

Siegurd stepped closer to the firelight.

“Zharoslav is tightening his hold,” he said. “Not openly. Not like before.”

Varka’s expression didn’t change—but something behind it sharpened.

“He’s learning,” Siegurd continued. “Adapting. He saw what happened in the throne room. He knows force alone won’t keep Illuga.”

Varka tilted his head slightly.

“And you think you know better?”

Siegurd’s answer came without hesitation.

“Yes.”

That hung there.

Heavy.

Varka studied him for a long moment.

Then, slowly:

“That’s a dangerous kind of confidence.”

Siegurd’s jaw tightened—but his voice stayed controlled.

“It isn’t confidence,” he said. “It’s observation.”

He gestured vaguely toward the camp.

“Look at him. He’s unraveling.”

Varka’s gaze flicked, briefly, toward Illuga’s tent.

Then back.

“And you think you’re the solution,” he said.

Siegurd didn’t flinch.

“I know what he needs.”

VARKA PUSHES BACK
That—finally—broke something loose.

Varka sat forward, flask set aside, elbows on his knees.

“Do you?” he asked quietly.

There was no mockery in it now.

Just… weight.

“Because I’ve seen men say that before,” he continued. “I’ve been that man before.”

Siegurd’s eyes narrowed slightly.

“And what did that make you?” he asked.

Varka’s mouth curved—not quite a smile.

“Someone who thought love meant knowing better than the other person,” he said.

A pause.

“Someone who wasn’t entirely wrong.”

Siegurd stilled.

That wasn’t the answer he expected.

THE TRUTH BEGINS TO SURFACE
“You think Zharoslav loves him,” Siegurd said.

It wasn’t a question.

Varka exhaled slowly.

“I think Zharoslav wants him,” he said. “Deeply. Obsessively.”

A beat.

“And I think that kind of wanting can look a lot like love if you’re standing too close to it.”

Siegurd’s voice sharpened.

“And you think what I feel is different?”

Varka met his gaze head-on.

“I think what you feel is cleaner.”

Siegurd blinked—just once.

Caught off guard.

Varka leaned back again, studying him.

“But don’t mistake ‘clean’ for ‘safe,’” he added.

SIEGURD REVEALS HIMSELF
Something in Siegurd shifted.

Not outwardly.

But the restraint tightened.

“You think I would harm him,” he said.

Varka shook his head.

“No,” he said simply.

A pause.

“I think you would shape him.”

Silence.

Siegurd’s expression didn’t change.

But the air did.

“And you wouldn’t?” he asked.

VARKA’S CONFESSION
Varka let out a long breath.

Then—

Quietly, without ceremony:

“I already did.”

Siegurd went still.

The fire cracked sharply between them.

“What?” he asked.

Varka’s gaze dropped briefly to the flames.

Then lifted again.

“Flins,” he said.

The name alone carried weight.

“I used pheromones on him.”

No hesitation.

No softening.

“I didn’t force him,” Varka added quickly. “But I tilted things. Made it easier for him to choose me.”

Siegurd stared at him.

Processing.

“You manipulated him,” he said flatly.

Varka nodded once.

“Yes.”

No defense.

No excuse.

Just truth.

THE MORAL DIVIDE
Siegurd’s voice hardened.

“And you think that makes you someone I should listen to?”

Varka’s gaze didn’t waver.

“I think it makes me someone who understands how thin the line is.”

A beat.

“Between loving someone… and wanting to make sure they stay.”

Siegurd’s hands clenched slightly at his sides.

“I would never—”

“Yes,” Varka cut in, calm but firm. “You would.”

Silence.

Heavy. Absolute.

“You just wouldn’t call it that,” Varka continued.

“You’d call it devotion.”

THE DANGEROUS TRUTH
Siegurd stepped closer now.

Close enough that the firelight caught the tension in his face.

“I give him everything,” he said.

“Gladly.”

“I ask for nothing.”

Varka’s eyes darkened.

“That’s the problem.”

Siegurd frowned.

“What?”

Varka leaned forward slightly.

“You think giving without asking means you don’t take,” he said.

A pause.

“But it does.”

Siegurd’s voice dropped.

“How?”

Varka held his gaze.

“Because eventually,” he said quietly, “he’ll feel like he owes you for it.”

The words settled between them.

Cold.

Unavoidable.

A LINE IS DRAWN
Siegurd didn’t speak for a long moment.

Then:

“I don’t want him to owe me anything.”

Varka nodded slowly.

“I believe you.”

A beat.

“But that doesn’t mean it won’t happen.”

Siegurd’s jaw tightened.

“And what would you have me do?” he asked.

“Step back? Let Zharoslav take him apart piece by piece?”

Varka’s expression shifted—something sharper now.

“No,” he said.

“Stand your ground.”

A pause.

“But don’t pretend you’re not fighting for something.”

Siegurd’s voice was quiet.

“I am.”

Varka tilted his head.

“Then own it.”

THE FINAL EXCHANGE
The wind picked up, tugging at cloaks, whispering through the trees.

Siegurd looked toward Illuga’s tent.

Then back.

“If it comes down to it,” he said, “I won’t step aside.”

Varka’s gaze was steady.

“I didn’t expect you to.”

A beat.

Siegurd hesitated—just slightly.

“And you?” he asked.

Varka leaned back again, expression unreadable.

“I already chose my fight,” he said.

AFTER
Siegurd turned away first.

But not in retreat.

In decision.

Varka watched him go.

Then reached for his flask again.

He didn’t drink.

He just held it.

Staring into the fire.

Quietly, to himself:

“…Flins is going to hate this.”

