VII. CINEMATIC SCENE INSERT — THRONE ROOM (DEFINITIVE)
The throne room of the Chernozar’s Palace was built to make men feel small.

It succeeded.

Black stone rose in cold, unbroken columns toward a ceiling lost in shadow. Frost clung to the high arches like lace, delicate and merciless. Between the pillars, nobles gathered in layered silks and furs, their voices low, expectant—like carrion birds sensing a wound before it was opened.

At the far end, upon the raised dais, sat Zharoslav.

He did not lean.

He did not shift.

He did not need to.

The throne held him as if it had been carved for no one else.

Red draped him—deep, consuming red—cut in sharp lines that mirrored the severity of his posture. One hand rested against the arm of the throne, fingers still, the signet ring catching the torchlight in slow, deliberate flashes.

He looked down the length of the hall.

Waiting.

The doors opened.

The sound echoed—long, hollow, final.

Illuga entered alone.

No herald announced him. No escort followed. The silence that greeted him was not respectful.

It was hungry.

He walked forward anyway.

Measured. Controlled. Each step placed with care against the polished stone, the soft fall of his boots the only sound that dared interrupt the stillness. His coat—red, always red now—caught the torchlight differently than Zharoslav’s. Softer. Warmer. As if it had been made not for display, but for survival.

Do not look at them.

He didn’t.

Not at the nobles whispering behind gloved hands. Not at the soldiers standing rigid along the walls. Not at Siegurd, who stood among them, too still—watching him with something that felt dangerously close to reverence.

Illuga’s gaze lifted only once.

To the throne.

To him.

Zharoslav did not greet him.

He only watched.

The space between them stretched. Not empty—never empty—but charged, coiled, waiting to snap.

Illuga stopped at the base of the dais.

For a moment, nothing happened.

Then—

“Speak.”

Zharoslav’s voice was quiet.

It did not need to be louder.

It carried anyway.

Illuga inhaled.

Slow.

Steady.

“My lord,” he began, the words precise, practiced, “I have come to request your support.”

A murmur rippled through the court.

Zharoslav did not react.

“Support,” he repeated, as though testing the word for weight. “You stand before my court… and you ask.”

Illuga held his gaze. “Yes.”

“For whom?”

“For Flins. And Varka.”

There it was.

The room shifted—subtle, but undeniable.

Zharoslav’s fingers moved.

Not much.

Just enough for the ring to catch the light again.

“And why,” he asked, almost idly, “would I lend my strength to men who do not belong to me?”

Illuga did not answer immediately.

Because the truth was dangerous.

Because the truth was him.

“They seek to end the Czarina’s will,” Illuga said at last. “And I intend to stand with them.”

A sharper stir this time. Less contained.

Zharoslav leaned back—barely—but it changed the air.

“Intent,” he said softly. “You speak as though your path is your own.”

Illuga’s jaw tightened.

“It is.”

The word landed.

Too firm.

Too fast.

Zharoslav smiled.

Not kindly.

“Is it?”

Silence closed in again.

Then—

“Ask properly.”

The words were gentle.

That made them worse.

Illuga stilled.

The court leaned forward—some openly now.

“What?”

Zharoslav’s gaze did not waver.

“You heard me.”

A pause.

Long enough to hurt.

“Ask properly.”

Illuga’s breath caught—not visibly, not fully—but enough.

“No,” he said.

Too quickly.

Too sharp.

A mistake.

Something flickered behind Zharoslav’s eyes.

Interest.

“Then you may leave.”

It was immediate.

Absolute.

Like a door slamming shut.

Illuga did not move.

Because he could not.

Because leaving meant—

No support. No army. No chance.

Because Flins would go anyway. Because Varka would follow. Because they would bleed for it.

And he would have done nothing.

His hands curled at his sides.

The room watched.

Waiting.

He hated them for it.

He hated him for it.

“…What do you want?”

The question was quieter now.

Zharoslav tilted his head slightly.

“Nothing you are not capable of giving.”

Cruel.

Precise.

Illuga closed his eyes.

Only for a second.

Then opened them again.

“Do not do this here.”

“Where else,” Zharoslav asked, “would it matter?”

A ripple of soft laughter—quickly smothered.

Illuga heard it.

Felt it.

Something inside him pulled tight.

“You would humiliate me,” he said, low, controlled, “for the sake of spectacle?”

Zharoslav leaned forward now.

At last.

And the entire room seemed to lean with him.

“For the sake of truth.”

A beat.

Then, softer—

“Or are you afraid of what you will choose?”

That—

That struck.

Illuga’s composure cracked—not outwardly, not fully—but enough that the breath he took after it was not steady.

Not controlled.

Human.

He looked at him.

Really looked.

And in that moment, there was no court.

No nobles.

No soldiers.

Just the two of them—and the memory of a night where he had not said no.

“…You know what I will choose,” Illuga said.

Zharoslav’s voice dropped.

“Yes.”

Silence.

Then—

Illuga stepped forward.

One step.

Then another.

Closer to the dais.

Closer to him.

The air thickened.

Someone shifted.

Someone exhaled.

No one spoke.

Illuga stopped.

Right at the first step of the throne.

He did not look away.

Not now.

Not anymore.

Slowly—

He lowered himself.

A murmur broke—sharp, disbelieving—but it died just as quickly.

Because no one had expected that.

One knee touched the stone.

Then the other.

Controlled.

Deliberate.

Chosen.

Illuga’s hands hovered—just for a moment—before settling against the floor.

Not yet fully lowered.

Not yet—

“Lower.”

Zharoslav did not raise his voice.

He didn’t have to.

Illuga’s fingers tightened against the stone.

Then—

He bent.

Further.

Until his palms lay flat.

Until his shoulders dipped.

Until the line of his body shifted into something unmistakable.

Submission.

The court went still.

Not laughing now.

Not whispering.

Watching.

Because this was no longer humiliation.

This was something else.

Something heavier.

Something that felt—

Sacred.

Illuga’s voice, when it came, was not steady.

“My lord,” he said, and the title meant something different now, “I am asking you.”

A pause.

Not long.

But enough to feel the weight of it.

“Please.”

The word fell—soft.

But it echoed.

Zharoslav did not move.

Not outwardly.

But something in him shifted—sharp, immediate, dangerous.

His hand tightened slightly against the arm of the throne.

“More.”

The command was almost a breath.

Illuga swallowed.

The court blurred at the edges.

He could feel them.

All of them.

Watching.

Judging.

Waiting for him to break.

He did.

Slowly.

Piece by piece.

He lowered further—until his forearms pressed to the cold stone.

Until his head bowed.

Until the shape he formed—intentional or not—mirrored something older.

A cross.

The Snezhnayan plea for mercy.

A gasp—soft, stunned—slipped from somewhere in the court.

The soldiers did not move.

But something in their posture changed.

Recognition.

Respect.

Because this was not weakness.

This was devotion to something beyond himself.

“To protect them,” Illuga said, the words breaking now, no longer clean, no longer controlled, “to end this—this rot—this—”

He stopped.

Started again.

“I am asking you to stand with us.”

Silence.

Then—quieter—

“I am asking you to stand with me.”

Zharoslav rose.

At last.

The sound of it—fabric shifting, boots against stone—cut through the room like a blade.

He descended the steps slowly.

Not rushing.

Never rushing.

Until he stood before him.

Close.

Too close.

He looked down at Illuga—not with mockery.

Not with pity.

With something far more dangerous.

Hunger.

His hand lifted.

Hovered.

Then settled lightly beneath Illuga’s chin.

Not forcing.

Not yet.

Just… there.

“Look at me.”

Illuga hesitated.

Then obeyed.

Of course he did.

Their eyes met.

And the room disappeared again.

Zharoslav’s voice dropped—low enough that only Illuga could truly hear it.

“You would give me this,” he said, almost thoughtfully, “for them.”

Illuga’s throat tightened.

“Yes.”

A pause.

Then—

“For you.”

That did it.

Something in Zharoslav snapped tight—dangerously close to breaking.

He exhaled slowly.

Controlled it.

Barely.

Then—

“Very well.”

The words were soft.

But they struck like iron.

“I will join them.”

The court erupted—voices rising, shock, protest—but it meant nothing.

Because the decision had already been made.

Zharoslav did not look away from Illuga as he spoke again.

“But understand this.”

His hand tightened—just slightly—at Illuga’s chin.

Not enough to hurt.

Enough to remind.

“You do not leave this place unchanged.”

A beat.

“And you do not leave me.”

Illuga did not answer.

Because he could not.

Because some part of him already knew—

He wouldn’t.

